description: A Trip to the Bottom of the World with Mouse is something of a travelogue about artist Frank Viva's visit to the Antarctic Peninsula. It's only something of a travelogue because it takes a little … license. And that license is Mouse, an anthropomorphic, well, mouse (and maybe the embodiment of Viva's seasickness, as described in his "About the Author") who asks, again and again, "Can we go home now?" The Boy in the Yellow Snowsuit (most likely the stand-in for Viva) persists with his trip--and it pays off, for both him and Mouse.
name: A Trip to the Bottom of the World

description:
Eerie is a one-shot horror comic book cover-dated January 1947 and published by Avon Periodicals as Eerie #1. Its creative team includes Joe Kubert and Fred Kida. The book's contents comprise six full-length horror feature stories and a 2-page humorous tale. The title went dormant for a number of years but returned to newsstands as Eerie #1 in 1951. The book holds the distinction of being the first true, stand-alone horror comic book and is credited with establishing the horror comics genre. The issue featured six stories that were fairly tame in the depiction of the gore and violence generally found in horror fiction.

The Eerie series was resurrected in 1951 again with 17 additional issues.
name: Eerie Comics

deck: Natsuyuki Rendezvous is a four volume series about Ryosuke helping a widow and her deceased husband reach closure.
description:
Proper Japanese Title: 夏雪ランデブー

Created by Haruka Kawachi, the manga series originally ran in Shodensha's magazine, Feel Young.

Published under the Feel Comics imprint.

Plot

The story revolves around a young man named Ryosuke Hazuki who falls in love with a young woman named Rokka Shimao who owns a flower shop. Ryosuke works at Rokka's flower shop in order to win her heart. However, it turns out that Rokka is a widow, and her deceased husband's ghost named Atsushi Shimao is not letting anyone near his wife.

Will Ryosuke be able to help Rokka and Atsushi move on?
name: Natsuyuki Rendezvous

description:
When the Upstarts overthrow the Hellfire Club in a bloody coup, the X-Men are caught in the middle! But their battle is interrupted when hundreds of escaped convicts arrive from the future — pursued by the mutant policeman called Bishop! Raised since childhood on the legends of the X-Men, how will this hard-edged fish out of water react to meeting his idols face-to-face? And what deadly portent of doom does Bishop carry with him?

Plus: Colossus’ long-lost brother Mikhail returns, but he’s gone completely mad — and that’s a “gift” he plans on sharing with the Morlocks! Storm and Forge’s romance is changed forever! And Professor X’s childhood secrets are revealed when the X-Men invade the Alamogordo research facility and battle Hazard!

Collecting Uncanny X-Men (1963) #281-293, and X-Men (1991) #12-13 and also material from #10-11, written by Whilce Portacio, Jim Lee, John Byrne, Scott Lobdell & Fabian Nicieza, pencilled by Whilce Portacio, John Romita Jr., Andy Kubert, Tom Raney, Rurik Tyler, Mark Texeira & Art Thibert, with a cover by Whilce Portacio.
